<%
  content_for :page_title, "How Our Rankings Work | The Greatest Games"
  content_for :meta_description, "Learn how The Greatest Games ranks video games using hundreds of curated lists, weighted scoring, and transparent algorithms."
%>

<div class="flex flex-col-reverse lg:flex-row gap-8">
  <%# Sidebar - shows first on mobile (via flex-col-reverse), right on desktop %>
  <aside class="lg:order-2 lg:w-72 shrink-0 flex flex-col gap-6">
    <div class="card bg-base-200">
      <div class="card-body">
        <h3 class="card-title text-lg">Join the Community</h3>
        <p class="text-sm">Want to talk games? We'd love to hear your takes.</p>
        <%= link_to "Join us on Discord", "https://discord.com/invite/8JE9fpMtZp",
            target: "_blank", rel: "noopener",
            class: "btn btn-primary btn-sm mt-2" %>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="card bg-base-200">
      <div class="card-body">
        <h3 class="card-title text-lg">Open Source</h3>
        <p class="text-sm">Our ranking algorithm and site code are fully open source.</p>
        <ul class="text-sm mt-2 space-y-1">
          <li><%= link_to "Ranking Algorithm (weighted_list_rank)", "https://github.com/ssherman/weighted_list_rank", target: "_blank", rel: "noopener", class: "link link-primary" %></li>
          <li><%= link_to "The Greatest (full site source)", "https://github.com/ssherman/the-greatest/", target: "_blank", rel: "noopener", class: "link link-primary" %></li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </aside>

  <%# Main content %>
  <div class="lg:order-1 flex-1 min-w-0">
    <h1 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold mb-6">How Our Rankings Work</h1>

    <p class="text-base-content/80 mb-8 text-lg leading-relaxed">
      Most "best of" aggregation sites just count how many lists something appears on and call it a day.
      We think that misses the point. Not all lists are created equal -- a carefully curated ranking by game
      critics carries different weight than a fan poll on a random forum. Our algorithm takes that into account.
    </p>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">The Algorithm</h2>
    <div class="space-y-4 mb-8 text-base-content/80 leading-relaxed">
      <p>
        Every list in our system starts with a base quality score. From there, we evaluate each list across
        several dimensions -- who voted, how many people voted, what the list covers, and whether it focuses
        on a specific niche or tries to be comprehensive. Lists that are more credible and broader in scope
        naturally carry more weight in the final rankings.
      </p>
      <p>
        Items that appear on multiple high-quality lists rise to the top. But we also give credit to items that
        land on a single exceptional list -- consensus matters, but so does expert recognition.
      </p>
    </div>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">What We Look At</h2>
    <p class="text-base-content/80 mb-4">
      Here are some of the factors our algorithm considers when evaluating a list:
    </p>

    <% if @static_penalties.any? %>
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mb-2">List Quality Signals</h3>
      <ul class="list-disc list-inside mb-6 text-base-content/80 space-y-1">
        <% @static_penalties.each do |penalty| %>
          <li><%= penalty.name %></li>
        <% end %>
      </ul>
    <% end %>

    <% if @dynamic_penalties.any? %>
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mb-2">Automatic Adjustments</h3>
      <ul class="list-disc list-inside mb-8 text-base-content/80 space-y-1">
        <% @dynamic_penalties.each do |penalty| %>
          <li><%= penalty.name %></li>
        <% end %>
      </ul>
    <% end %>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">Solving for Recency Bias</h2>
    <p class="text-base-content/80 mb-8 leading-relaxed">
      One of the trickiest problems in ranking anything is recency bias. A "best games of all time" list
      published in 2024 is naturally going to skew toward games from the last decade or two -- the voters simply
      haven't played everything from the 1980s. We address this with what we call the List Dates Penalty.
      When a game was released long before the list was published, we gradually reduce how much that
      list-placement counts toward the game's ranking. This way, a classic game doesn't get unfairly penalized
      just because it wasn't top-of-mind for recent voters.
    </p>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">By the Numbers</h2>
    <div class="stats stats-vertical md:stats-horizontal shadow mb-8 w-full">
      <div class="stat">
        <div class="stat-title">Active Lists</div>
        <div class="stat-value"><%= number_with_delimiter(@active_lists_count) %></div>
      </div>
      <div class="stat">
        <div class="stat-title">Ranked Items</div>
        <div class="stat-value"><%= number_with_delimiter(@ranked_items_count) %></div>
      </div>
      <div class="stat">
        <div class="stat-title">Median Items per List</div>
        <div class="stat-value"><%= @median_list_count %></div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">Open Source</h2>
    <p class="text-base-content/80 mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      We believe in transparency. Our ranking algorithm is open source -- you can read the code,
      suggest improvements, or even run it yourself.
    </p>
    <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-base-content/80 space-y-1">
      <li><%= link_to "Ranking Algorithm (weighted_list_rank gem)", "https://github.com/ssherman/weighted_list_rank", target: "_blank", rel: "noopener", class: "link link-primary" %></li>
      <li><%= link_to "The Greatest (full site source)", "https://github.com/ssherman/the-greatest/", target: "_blank", rel: "noopener", class: "link link-primary" %></li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</div>
